{{Infobox scientist | name = Cesare Arzelà | image = Cesare Arzelà.jpg | image_size = | caption = A [[relief]] portraying Cesare Arzelà at the Mathematics Department of [[Bologna University]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1847|03|06|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Santo Stefano di Magra]], [[Province of La Spezia|La Spezia]], [[Italy]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1912|03|12|1847|04|06|df=yes}} | death_place = Santo Stefano di Magra, [[Province of La Spezia|La Spezia]], Italy | nationality = [[Italy|Italian]] | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[Scuola Normale Superiore]], [[University of Florence]], [[University of Bologna]] | alma_mater = [[Scuola Normale Superiore]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Enrico Betti]] | doctoral_students = [[Leonida Tonelli]] | known_for = [[Arzelà-Ascoli theorem]], contributions to [[Functional analysis]], [[mathematical analysis]] | awards = }} '''Cesare Arzelà''' (6 March 1847 – 15 March 1912) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[mathematician]] who taught at the [[University of Bologna]] and is recognized for his contributions in the [[Functions (mathematics)|theory of functions]], particularly for his characterization of [[Sequence (mathematics)|sequences]] of [[continuous function]]s, generalizing the one given earlier by [[Giulio Ascoli]] in the [[Arzelà-Ascoli theorem]].
==Life== He was a pupil of the [[Scuola Normale Superiore]] of [[Pisa]] where he graduated in 1869. Arzelà came from a poor household; therefore he could not start his study until 1871, when he studied in Pisa under [[Enrico Betti]] and [[Ulisse Dini]].
He was working in [[Florence]] (from 1875) and in 1878 obtained the Chair of Algebra at the [[University of Palermo]].
After that he became a professor in 1880 at the [[University of Bologna]] at the department of analysis. He conducted research in the field of [[Functions (mathematics)|theory of functions]]. His most famous student was [[Leonida Tonelli]].
In 1889 he generalized the [[Giulio Ascoli|Ascoli]] theorem to [[Arzelà–Ascoli theorem]], an important [[theorem]] in theory of functions.
He was a member of the [[Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei]], and of several other academies.
