{{notability|Academics|date=June 2017}}
'''Franz Harress''' (died circa 1915) was a mathematician and contemporary of [[Albert Einstein]] and is best known for his experiment on the propagation of light in a rotating glass device. This experiment sparked an argument between [[Einstein]] and [[Paul Harzer]] related to the theory of [[Special Relativity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://einsteinpapers.press.princeton.edu/vol6-doc/56?ajax|title=Volume 6: The Berlin Years: Writings, 1914-1917 page 28|website=einsteinpapers.press.princeton.edu}}</ref>
Harress was a student of Professor Otto Julius Heinrich Knopf at [[Friedrich Schiller Universität Jena|Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena]] in 1912.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=52435&fChrono=1|title=Otto Knopf - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu}}</ref> His dissertation was "Die Geschwindigkeit des Lichtes in bewegten Körpern" ("The speed of light in moving bodies").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=52927|title=Franz Harress - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu}}</ref> His work on the [[Sagnac effect]] was analyzed by [[Max von Laue]] in his 1920 paper "On the Experiment of F. Harress."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:On_the_Experiment_of_F._Harress|title=On the Experiment of F. Harress - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.m.wikisource.org}}</ref>

